Date:  0/0/1937
Source:  Dictionary of Slang
Author:  PARTRIDGE
Vol / Page:  347
Edition:
Quote:  Graft. 2. To work; esp. to work hard: coll., mostly Australia and New Zealand: from ca. 1870. Earlier (ca. 1855-80), to go to work: English only (H., 1st ed.). Esp. in where are you grafting? Prob.  ext grave, to dig, perhaps influenced by the gardening graft and even by craft (as in arts and crafts).
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1944
Source:  US War Dept. Short Guide to NZ
Author:
Vol / Page:  37
Edition:
Quote:  For instance, to `graft' means to work hard, and to be `crook' is to be ill or out of sorts.
